    gw.api.webservice.ObjectFilter
    The ObjectFilter class is deprecated. Instead, rewrite integration code as custom web service APIs for each integration point, defining most application logic within the web service. Before this release, external code requested large objects and used ObjectFilter to define arbitrary fields to return so that the data transfer is not too large. Instead, design your new custom web services to return only what is needed. You might want to create new Gosu classes or non-persistent business entities for some integration points to encapsulate data passed to the web service or returned from the web service.

    gw.testharness.ProductType
    Convert your test to a V3 test within a test module that depends on the module you are testing. For example, if intending to test something in cc-locale-ja-jp then put the test in a module cc-locale-ja-jp-test that depends on cc-locale-ja-jp. In the case of MultiApp tests, write a generic V3 test (but ending with TestBase instead) in pl-test and then write simple V3 test classes that extend it within each xx-test module.
  • Deprecated Exceptions 
    Exceptions and Description
    gw.xml.parser2.ConfigParserException
    gw.pl.external.GenericCheckedException
    External entities are deprecated. Please use the new Java API instead.
  • Deprecated Annotation Types 
    Annotation Type and Description
    gw.testharness.Disabled
    Please do not use this annotation to disable tests. Alternatives:
    • Fix the test.
    • Delete the test.
    • KnownBreak the test. Note that "KnownBreak" tests are executed and their failures are ignored, while "Disabled" tests are not executed at all. Therefore, changing a "Disabled" test to "KnownBreak" may cause other tests in the suite to behave differently, if the "Disabled" test produces side effects that are visible to other tests.
    gw.testharness.EnableExtJs
    will be removed once ExtJs feature completes and enables by default
    gw.testharness.IncludeModules
    gw.testharness.IncludeModulesBeforeEnterRunLevel
    gw.lang.InternalAPI
    This annotation is a temporary indicator of members on public types that are for internal use only. Such members should be moved off the public type as soon as possible. See https://confluence.guidewire.com/display/MOD/Removal+of+@InternalAPI+members+from+public+APIs for more details.
    gw.pl.external.Invocation
    External entities are deprecated. Please use the new Java API instead.
    gw.testharness.Nondeterministic
    Please do not use this annotation to ignore broken, non-deterministic tests. Instead, use KnownBreak and explicitly force the test to fail at the end of the test.

    gw.api.web.util.PCBigDecimalUtil.calculatePercentageOf(BigDecimal, BigDecimal, int)
    in 9.0.3. Usage of method PCBigDecimalUtil.calculatePercentage(BigDecimal, BigDecimal) is preferable to have the same scale of calculation percentages across PC. If percentage result need to be displayed on UI scaling might be applied afterwards
    gw.api.web.util.PCCurrencyAmountUtil.calculatePercentageOf(MonetaryAmount, MonetaryAmount, int)
    in 9.0.3. Usage of method PCCurrencyAmountUtil.calculatePercentageOf(MonetaryAmount, MonetaryAmount) is preferable to have the same scale of calculation percentages across PC. Usage of this method causes losing precision when result of percentage calculation is applied to amount, e.g.: 
     

 MonetaryAmount total = new MonetaryAmount("12226.01 USD");
 MonetaryAmount portion = new MonetaryAmount("555.55 USD");
 BigDecimal percentage = calculatePercentageOf(portion, total, portion.getAmount().scale());
 // percentage is 4.54, but should be 4.544..
 // apply it to some amount
 MonetaryAmount amount = calculatePercentage(new MonetaryAmount("321654 USD"), percentage);
 // result is 14603.09 usd but should be 14615.96 usd
    Result is really dependent to calculated amounts and might have a big impact for calculation. Method PCCurrencyAmountUtil.calculatePercentageOf(MonetaryAmount, MonetaryAmount) will calculate percentage with scale 6.
    gw.api.web.util.PCCurrencyAmountUtil.calculatePercentageOf(MonetaryAmount, MonetaryAmount, int, RoundingMode)
    in 9.0.3. Usage of method PCCurrencyAmountUtil.calculatePercentageOf(MonetaryAmount, MonetaryAmount, RoundingMode) is preferable to have the same scale of calculation percentages across PC. Usage of this method causes losing precision when result of percentage calculation is applied to amount, e.g.: 
     

 MonetaryAmount total = new MonetaryAmount("12226.01 USD");
 MonetaryAmount portion = new MonetaryAmount("555.55 USD");
 BigDecimal percentage = calculatePercentageOf(portion, total, portion.getAmount().scale(), RoundingMode.HALF_UP);
 // percentage is 4.54, but should be 4.544..
 // apply it to some amount
 MonetaryAmount amount = calculatePercentage(new MonetaryAmount("321654 USD"), percentage);
 // result is 14603.09 usd but should be 14615.96 usd
    Result is really dependent to calculated amounts and might have a big impact for calculation. Method PCCurrencyAmountUtil.calculatePercentageOf(MonetaryAmount, MonetaryAmount, RoundingMode) will calculate percentage with scale 6.

 <BizRulesPermissions>
   <RuleSubtypeAccessProfile entity="FooRule">
     <RuleViewPermission permission="fooruleview"/>
     <RuleEditPermission permission="fooruleedit"/>
     <RuleDeployPermission permission="fooruledeploy"/>
     <RuleImportPermission permission="fooruleimport"/>
     <RuleApprovePermission permission="fooruleapprove"/>

    gw.pl.persistence.type.EntityTypeReference.newInstance(Bundle)
    This method is not safe in general, because it doesn't account for required parameters, nor does it respect the intended visibility of entity constructors. If T is known at compile time, then use the entity constructor instead, if available. If it is not available, then either this entity is abstract or is not intended to be constructed directly by user code. If T is not known at compile time, then use Bundle.newBeanInstance(gw.entity.IEntityType) instead, but note that this method should be used with caution.
    gw.pl.persistence.type.EntityTypeReference.newInstance(Bundle, TypeKey)
    This method is not safe in general, because it doesn't account for required parameters, nor does it respect the intended visibility of entity constructors. Furthermore, it is not type-safe, as there is no guarantee that the subtype parameter is actually a subtype of T. If the subtype is known at compile time, then use the entity constructor instead, if available. If it is not available, then this entity is not intended to be constructed directly by user code. If the subtype is not known at compile time, then use Bundle.newBeanInstance(gw.entity.IEntityType) instead, but note that this method should be used with caution.

    This method is not safe in general, because it doesn't account for required parameters, nor does it respect the intended visibility of entity constructors. If T is known at compile time, then use the entity constructor instead, if available. If it is not available, then either this entity is abstract or is not intended to be constructed directly by user code.
    gw.pl.persistence.type.EffDatedEntityTypeReference.newInstance(R, TypeKey)
    This method is not safe in general, because it doesn't account for required parameters, nor does it respect the intended visibility of entity constructors. Furthermore, it is not type-safe, as there is no guarantee that the subtype parameter is actually a subtype of T. If the subtype is known at compile time, then use the entity constructor instead, if available. If it is not available, then this entity is not intended to be constructed directly by user code.
